{"key":"processedPost-9002338","value":{"id":9002338,"first":9002135,"last":9002554,"when":1222710917,"utime":"09/29/08 08:55 PM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br />I have not regulated the humidity w/ a hygrometer, but I dont have condensation on the walls at all. </blockquote><br />Condensation has nothing to do with humidity.&nbsp; It only indicates a temperature differential, which is rare with mini-greenhouses.<br />There shouldn't always be moisture on the surface of the casing layers.&nbsp; Proper primordia formation depends on a certain rate of evaporation of moisture away from the casing or substrate, thus if it's always wet, that evaporation is not occurring.&nbsp; Even at 99% humidity, if you have enough fresh air supply, moisture will evaporate from your casing layers.<br />Put your humidifier on a timer so that it doesn't run all the time.&nbsp; I suspect that too much mist is going into the greenhouse, and if it all isn't absorbed into the air, it falls on the trays, keeping them over saturated.<br />RR","title":"Re: Fruiting Conditions out of whack? (picture attatched)"}}